\cf8 \cb9 \uc0\u10095  \cf6 I'm sharing my project proposal with you. We need to build this together in \cf3   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 R/Shiny or what you deem best. Product Description\cf3                               \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 SkiSmart is a web application designed for recreational skiers who want to plan\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9  a ski trip in the United States without manually checking multiple websites to\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9  check resort, weather, snow, and road conditions. This tool helps them make a \cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 decision by answering, \'93Where should I ski, and how should I get there?\'94. \cf3       \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 The user enters key inputs and preferences, such as their starting location, \cf3    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 maximum drive time they are willing to make and ski experience and landscape \cf3    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 preferences, and the tool returns a ranked list of ski resorts with the best \cf3    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 match. The ranking is based on a resort scoring metric that accounts for user \cf3   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 preferences while also considering aspects like current snow conditions, number\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9  of lifts open, and forecasted weather for the upcoming weekend. Rather than \cf3    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 replacing any single existing data source, SkiSmart synthesizes information \cf3     \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 that is currently scattered across resort websites, weather services, and state\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9  department of transportation portals into a single, easily accessible and \cf3      \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 actionable recommendation. Alongside the recommendations,  the website displays\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9  graphics on the weather and snowfall conditions, as well as a map with the \cf3     \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 suggested resorts. This constitutes the first layer of the product. \cf3             \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Once this works flawlessly, we aim to incorporate a route and map-planning tool\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9  as a second layer. This would display the best route possible taking into \cf3      \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 account road closures and weather conditions by modeling a route risk index. \cf3    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 This will also act as a feasibility check for suggested resorts, ensuring that \cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 it is possible to reach the resorts given the conditions. The initial scope \cf3     \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 covers resorts in Colorado, which was chosen because of data availability and \cf3   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 API access. However, we plan on expanding our product to additional states if \cf3   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 time and data permits.\cf3                                                           \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 There are some remaining questions that will be further specified as the \cf3        \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 project develops; such as how far in advance the recommendations should be \cf3      \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 available. For now, we are thinking about making our data product available for\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9  up to 10 days into the future for data availability reasons and reliable \cf3       \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 weather forecasts.\cf3                                                               \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Target Capabilities\cf3                                                              \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 In addition to the required user input, we are aiming to incorporate two \cf3        \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 capabilities in our data product:\cf3                                                \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 API Integration  \cf3                                                                \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 The core of the pipeline is the consumption of multiple live APIs at runtime. \cf3   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Other than the manually constructed ski-resort database, no data is \cf3             \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 pre-downloaded or stored statically. Every time a user submits their location, \cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 the app fetches current snow depth, temperature, and precipitation forecasts \cf3    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 from the Open-Meteo API; drive time and distance from the OpenRouteService API;\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9  and road condition advisories from Colorado DOT feeds. This multi-source \cf3       \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 integration makes the product a useful data pipeline rather than a static \cf3       \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 dashboard. The integration of the API\'92s is the first target capability we will \cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 prioritise.\cf3                                                                      \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 GenAI Model  \cf3                                                                    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Second, we are hoping to include a GenAI model, after successfully integrating \cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 the above stated API\'92s. Once the data is assembled and scored for each resort, \cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 a large language model generates a short plain-language summary for each \cf3        \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 recommendation. This would make the information even more accessible for the \cf3    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 user, as they do not have to interpret raw numbers. The LLM would use the data \cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 input and consolidate it into a practical one-paragraph briefing. For instance,\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9  the generated summary could look like this: "Roads to Beaver Creek are \cf3         \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 currently under a winter weather advisory in Eagle County. However, 80% of \cf3      \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 lifts are open and 6 inches of fresh snow fell in the past 48 hours. If you can\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9  leave before 7am to beat the advisory window, conditions look strong."\cf3          \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Data Source(s)\cf3                                                                   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Static Resort Database (manually curated) A structured dataset of 25-30 major \cf3   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Colorado ski resorts compiled from OnTheSnow, Uncovercolorado and official \cf3      \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 resort websites. Fields include coordinates, elevation, vertical drop, trail \cf3    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 counts by difficulty, terrain features, season dates, lift ticket prices, and \cf3   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 pass affiliations. Built once, version-controlled in the repository, and chosen\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9  over live scraping for reliability and reproducibility.\cf3                         \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Open-Meteo (open-meteo.com) Free, no API key. Provides live hourly forecasts \cf3    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 (snowfall, snow depth, temperature, wind) at resort coordinates and along the \cf3   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 driving route. Also used for historical climatological data as a probabilistic \cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 fallback for trips planned beyond the 14-day forecast window. Queried via HTTP \cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 at runtime using coordinates sampled along the route and at each resort.\cf3         \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Colorado DOT 511 API (cotrip.org) Free, requires registration. Provides \cf3         \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 real-time road conditions for Colorado highways including closure status and \cf3    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 chain law requirements by segment. Primary source for route feasibility on the \cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 I-70 mountain corridor.\cf3                                                          \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Colorado Avalanche Information Center (avalanche.state.co.us) Free, no key. \cf3     \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Daily avalanche forecasts by zone as structured JSON, including danger rating \cf3   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 (Low\'96Extreme) and elevation band breakdowns. Zone membership is determined by \cf3   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 spatially joining route sample points against CAIC zone polygons.\cf3                \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 OpenRouteService (openrouteservice.org) Free tier, API key required. Returns \cf3    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 driving route geometry as GeoJSON with elevation profile. Used to generate \cf3      \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 routes from user origin to each candidate resort, from which points are sampled\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9  for condition queries.\cf3                                                          \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Nominatim / OpenStreetMap Free, no key. Geocodes user origin to coordinates for\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9  routing and distance calculations.\cf3                                              \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Anthropic / OpenAI API Minimal cost (~$1\'962 total). Final synthesis layer \'97 \cf3      \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 receives structured pipeline output and generates a plain-language trip \cf3         \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 briefing, safety advisories, and temperature-calibrated gear list. All \cf3          \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 analytical work is completed upstream before the LLM is called.\cf3                  \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Technical Plan\cf3                                                                   \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 USER INPUTS\cf3                                                                      \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Origin city, travel dates, group size, skier ability (per person), terrain \cf3      \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 preferences, resort vibe, vehicle type, chains (yes/no), max drive time, risk \cf3   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 tolerance, season pass (None/Ikon/Epic), arrival/departure time window\cf3           \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9         \uc0\u8595 \cf3                                                                        \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 STAGE 1 \'97 RESORT SCORING\cf3                                                         \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Load static resort database (manually built CSV, ~30 Colorado resorts)\cf3           \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Fetch per resort at runtime:\cf3                                                     \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Open-Meteo: snow depth, snowfall last 72hrs, temp trend, trip date forecast\cf3  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - CAIC: avalanche danger rating for resort zone\cf3                                \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Compute weighted score per resort:\cf3                                               \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Snow score: f(base depth, recent snowfall, forecast)\cf3                         \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Terrain match: f(trail difficulty distribution vs. group ability levels)\cf3     \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Conditions risk: f(avalanche rating, storm forecast)\cf3                         \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Estimated terrain open: rule-based formula\cf3                                   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9     f(base depth, recent snowfall)\cf3                                               \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9     \uc0\u8594  "~65% of terrain likely open"\cf3                                              \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Rank resorts \uc0\u8594  top 3 candidates\cf3                                                  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9         \uc0\u8595 \cf3                                                                        \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 STAGE 2 \'97 ROUTE RISK SCORING\cf3                                                     \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 For each candidate resort:\cf3                                                       \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 OpenRouteService \uc0\u8594  route geometry + elevation\cf3                                    \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Sample 20 points along route\cf3                                                     \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 At each point query:\cf3                                                             \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - CDOT 511: closure status, chain controls\cf3                                     \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Open-Meteo: hourly snow/wind forecast\cf3                                        \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - CAIC: avalanche zone membership\cf3                                              \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Compute risk score per segment:\cf3                                                  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   risk = w1*(snow forecast)\cf3                                                      \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9        + w2*(closure status)\cf3                                                     \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9        + w3*(avalanche danger)\cf3                                                   \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9        + w4*(elevation)\cf3                                                          \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9        + w5*(vehicle penalty)\cf3                                                    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Weights scaled by user risk tolerance\cf3                                            \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9         \uc0\u8595 \cf3                                                                        \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 STAGE 3 \'97 FEASIBILITY + FALLBACK\cf3                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Hard blocks \uc0\u8594  reject resort:\cf3                                                     \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Road closed, no alternate\cf3                                                    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Avalanche HIGH/EXTREME on route\cf3                                              \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Resort closed for season\cf3                                                     \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Drive exceeds user maximum\cf3                                                   \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Soft flags \uc0\u8594  show warning:\cf3                                                       \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Chains required, none available\cf3                                              \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Storm during drive window\cf3                                                    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Snow base below 30"\cf3                                                          \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Primary resort blocked \uc0\u8594  try #2\cf3                                                  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Resort #2 blocked \uc0\u8594  try #3\cf3                                                       \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Display all rejections with reasons\cf3                                              \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9         \uc0\u8595 \cf3                                                                        \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 STAGE 4 \'97 DEPARTURE OPTIMIZER\cf3                                                    \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 For each hour in user's departure window:\cf3                                        \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   Re-score route using hourly forecast\cf3                                           \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   Estimate arrival with conditions penalty\cf3                                       \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Find optimal window:\cf3                                                             \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   Minimize risk score\cf3                                                            \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   Subject to: arrive before lifts close,\cf3                                         \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   return before next storm, within\cf3                                               \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   user's flexibility\cf3                                                             \cb1 \
\cb9                                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Output: recommended departure + return\cf3                                           \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9         window, hourly risk curve\cf3                                                \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9         \uc0\u8595 \cf3                                                                        \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 STAGE 5 \'97 LLM SYNTHESIS\cf3                                                          \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Input: structured JSON of all above\cf3                                              \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Output:\cf3                                                                          \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Plain language trip recommendation\cf3                                           \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Why other resorts were rejected\cf3                                              \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Key safety advisories\cf3                                                        \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Gear + packing list calibrated\cf3                                               \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9     to actual forecast temperatures\cf3                                              \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9         \uc0\u8595 \cf3                                                                        \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 OUTPUT DASHBOARD\cf3                                                                 \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Map:\cf3                                                                             \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   Route colored green/yellow/red by risk\cf3                                         \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   Avalanche zones as shaded overlays\cf3                                             \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   Resort pins with score badges\cf3                                                  \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   Rejected resorts marked with reason\cf3                                            \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 Panels:\cf3                                                                          \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Recommended resort + score breakdown\cf3                                         \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Estimated terrain open (with caveat)\cf3                                         \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Departure timing chart\cf3                                                       \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Flagged route segments\cf3                                                       \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9   - Gear checklist\cf3                                                               \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 . I want you to first read and absorb this and then i'll give further \cf3           \cb1 \
\cf6 \cb9 instructions on how to proceed\cf3                                                   \cb1 \
\
\cf6 \uc0\u9210 \cf3  I've read the full proposal. Here's my understanding of what SkiSmart is:\
\
  
\f1\b Core
\f0\b0  
\f1\b Problem:
\f0\b0  Recreational skiers have to manually check multiple sources\
  (resort sites, weather, road conditions) to plan a trip. SkiSmart synthesizes\
  these into a single ranked recommendation.\
\
  
\f1\b Two-Layer
\f0\b0  
\f1\b Architecture:
\f0\b0 \
  1. 
\f1\b Layer
\f0\b0  
\f1\b 1
\f0\b0  \'97 Resort scoring + recommendation (MVP)\
  2. 
\f1\b Layer
\f0\b0  
\f1\b 2
\f0\b0  \'97 Route planning with risk index and feasibility checks\
\
  
\f1\b 5-Stage
\f0\b0  
\f1\b Pipeline:
\f0\b0 \
  1. Resort Scoring (Open-Meteo + CAIC + static CSV)\
  2. Route Risk Scoring (OpenRouteService + CDOT 511 + Open-Meteo)\
  3. Feasibility + Fallback logic (hard blocks vs. soft warnings)\
  4. Departure Optimizer (hourly risk curve, optimal departure window)\
  5. LLM Synthesis (plain-language briefing + gear list)\
\
  
\f1\b Data
\f0\b0  
\f1\b Sources:
